A '''huarizo''' is a cross between a male [[llama]] and a female [[alpaca]]. The most common hybrid between South American camelids,<ref>{{cite book|author1=A. Rosati|author2=A. Tewolde|author3=C. Mosconi|title=WAAP Book Of The Year 2003: A Review on Developments and Research in Livestock Systems|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KgIvAoqlzUIC&pg=PA188|accessdate=6 June 2012|date=30 September 2004|publisher=Wageningen Academic Pub|isbn=978-90-76998-47-3|page=188}}</ref> huarizo tend to be much smaller than llamas, with their fibre being longer.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Martina Gerken|author2=Carlo Renieri|title=South American Camelids Research: Proceedings of the 4th European Symposium on South American Camelids and DECAMA European Seminar, Göttingen, 7-9 October 2004|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Jq6deKJq0CMC|accessdate=6 June 2012|year=2006|publisher=Wageningen Academic Pub|isbn=978-90-76998-98-5|page=283}}</ref> Huarizo are sterile in the wild, but recent genetic research conducted at the  [[University of Minnesota Rochester]] suggests that it may be possible to preserve fertility with minimal [[genetic engineering|genetic modification]].{{citation needed|date=June 2012}}

