'''Domestic ducks''' are [[duck]]s that are raised for [[meat]], [[egg (food)|egg]]s and [[Down feathers|down]]. Many ducks are also kept for show, as pets, or for their ornamental value. Almost all varieties of [[domestication|domestic]] duck apart from the [[Muscovy duck]] (''Cairina moschata'') are descended from the [[mallard]] (''Anas platyrhynchos'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://digimorph.org/specimens/anas_platyrhynchos/skull/ |title=Anas platyrhynchos, Domestic Duck; DigiMorph Staff - The University of Texas at Austin |publisher=Digimorph.org |date= |accessdate=23 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Sy Montgomery |url=http://www.britannica.com/eb/topic-360302/mallard |title=Mallard; Encyclopædia Britannica |publisher=Britannica.com |date= |accessdate=23 December 2012}}</ref>

== Domestication ==
{{further|Domestication|List of duck breeds}}
[[File:Egyptian - Vase in the Shape of a Duck - Walters 48421 - Profile.jpg|thumb|left|Ducks were common in [[Ancient Egypt]], as depicted in this 3rd century BC [[faience]] vase.]]

[[Mallard]] ducks were first domesticated in [[Southeast Asia]] at least 4000 years ago, during the [[Neolithic|Neolithic Age]], and were also farmed by the [[Demography of the Roman Empire|Romans]] in [[Europe]], and the [[Malays (ethnic group)|Malays]] in [[Asia]].<ref name=":5">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=fXJBBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA123 |title=Bird Brains: Inside the Strange Minds of Our Fine Feathered Friends |last=Titlow |first=Budd |date=2013 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-0-762-79770-7}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=MfrdBcKd79wC&pg=PA7 |title=Ducks, Geese and Swans: General chapters, species accounts (Anhima to Salvadorina)|last=Kear |first=Janet |date=2005 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-198-61008-3}}</ref> In [[ancient Egypt]], ducks were captured in nets and then bred in captivity.<ref>{{cite book |year=1998 |author=Manuelian, Peter der |title=Egypt: The World of the Pharaohs |location=Cologne, Germany|publisher=Könemann |isbn=978-3-89508-913-8 |page=381}}</ref> During the [[Ming Dynasty]], the [[Peking duck]]—mallards force-fed on grains, making them larger— was known to have good genetic characteristics.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=48sgHPrbUiQC&pg=PA3 |title=Domestic Duck Production: Science and Practice |last=Cherry |first=Peter |last2=Morris |first2=Trevor Raymond |date=2008 |publisher=CABI |isbn=9781845934415}}</ref>

Almost all varieties of domestic duck except the [[muscovy duck|muscovy]] have been derived from the [[mallard]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=hW6BCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA9&dq |title=Poultry Behaviour and Welfare|last=Appleby|first=Michael C.|last2=Mench|first2=Joy A.|last3=Hughes|first3=Barry O. |date=2004 |publisher=CABI |isbn=978-0-851-99667-7}}</ref> Domestication has greatly altered their characteristics. Domestic ducks are mostly [[Polygamy|polygamous]], where wild mallards are [[monogamy|monogamous]]. Domestic ducks have lost the mallard's territorial behaviour, and are less aggressive than mallards.<ref name=Piggott>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=AQ89AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA407 |title=The Agrarian History of England and Wales: Volume 1, Part 1, Prehistory |last=Piggott  |first=Stuart |last2=Thirsk |first2=Joan |date=February 1981|publisher=Cambridge University Press Archive |isbn=978-0-521-08741-4}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://digimorph.org/specimens/anas_platyrhynchos/skull/ |title=Anas platyrhynchos, Domestic Duck |author=DigiMorph Staff –The University of Texas at Austin |date=2004 |publisher=Digimorph.org |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161127010859/http://digimorph.org/specimens/anas_platyrhynchos/skull/ |archive-date=27 November 2016 |dead-url=yes |accessdate=2012-12-23 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Despite these differences, domestic ducks frequently mate with wild mallard, producing fully fertile [[hybrid (biology)|hybrid]] offspring.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=xtEGCAAAQBAJ&pg=PT212 |title=Elements of Ethology: A textbook for agricultural and veterinary students |last=Wood-Gush |first=D. |date=2012 |publisher=Springer |isbn=978-9-400-95931-6}}</ref>

== Farming ==
[[File:Taiwanese duck farm.jpg|thumb|left|A duck farm in Taiwan]]

Ducks have been farmed for thousands of years.<ref>{{cite book |title= The Cambridge World History of Food |last1=Kiple |first1=Kenneth F. |last2=Ornelas |first2=Kriemhild Coneè |year=2000 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-40214-9 |oclc=44541840}}</ref> In the [[Western world]], they are not as popular as the [[chicken]], because chickens have much more white lean meat and are easier to keep confined, making the total price much lower for [[chicken meat]], whereas [[duck (food)|duck]] is comparatively expensive. While popular in ''[[haute cuisine]]'', duck appears less frequently in the mass-market food industry and restaurants in the lower price range. However, ducks are more popular in [[China]] and there they are raised extensively.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}

Ducks are farmed for their meat, [[egg]]s, and [[Down feather|down]]. A minority of ducks are also kept for ''[[foie gras]]'' production. The [[blood as food|blood]] of ducks slaughtered for meat is also collected in some regions and is used as an ingredient in many cultures' dishes. Their eggs are blue-green to white, depending on the breed.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}

Ducks can be kept [[free range]], in cages, in barns, or in [[battery farming|batteries]]. Ducks enjoy access to swimming water, but do not require it to survive. They should be fed a [[grain]] and [[insect]] diet. It is a popular misconception that ducks should be fed [[bread]]; bread has limited nutritional value and can be deadly when fed to developing ducklings. Ducks should be monitored for [[avian influenza]], as they are especially prone to infection with the dangerous [[H5N1]] strain.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}

The females of many breeds of domestic ducks are unreliable at sitting their eggs and raising their young. Exceptions include the [[Rouen duck]] and especially the [[Muscovy duck]]. It has been a custom on farms for centuries to put duck eggs under [[chicken#Current|broody hens]] for hatching; nowadays this role is often played by an [[wikt:incubator|incubator]]. However, young ducklings rely on their mothers for a supply of [[preen oil]] to make them waterproof; a chicken hen does not make as much preen oil as a female duck, and an incubator makes none. Once the duckling grows its own feathers, it produces preen oil from the sebaceous gland near the base of its tail.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.zooenc.eu/en/ducks/ | title=Ducks - Poultry Breeds Encyclopedia}}</ref>

== Pets and ornamentals ==
[[File:Duckling - domestic duck.jpg|thumb|upright|Domestic duckling]]
[[File:Cairina moschata 001.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Muscovy duck]] (drake shown) is the only domestic breed not derived from the [[mallard]].]]

Domestic ducks can be kept as pets, in a garden or backyard, generally with a pond or deep water dish. If they are given access to a pond, they dabble in the mud, dredging out and eating wildlife and [[frog spawn]], and swallow adult [[frog]]s and [[toad]]s up to the size of the [[common frog]] ''Rana temporaria'', as they have been bred to be much bigger than wild ducks, with a waterline length (base of neck to base of tail) of up to {{convert|1|ft|cm}}; the wild [[mallard]]'s waterline length is about {{convert|6|in|cm}}. Protection from predators such as [[fox]]es and [[hawk]]s is required.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}<ref>{{cite book|last1=Link|first1=Kimberly|title=The Ultimate Pet Duck Guidebook|date=2014|publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform|isbn=978-1500344771}}</ref>

Ducks are also kept for their ornamental value. Breeds have been developed with crests and tufts or striking plumage, for exhibition in competitions.<ref>{{cite news|title=The best ducks to keep in your garden: in pictures|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gardening/9139166/The-best-ducks-to-keep-in-your-garden-in-pictures.html|accessdate=28 June 2017|work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref>

== In culture ==

=== In children's stories ===
[[File:Jemima1.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Beatrix Potter]]'s 1908 ''[[The Tale of Jemima Puddle-Duck]]'']]

The domestic duck has appeared numerous times in children's stories. [[Beatrix Potter]]'s ''[[The Tale of Jemima Puddle-Duck]]'' was published by [[Frederick Warne & Co]] in 1908. One of Potter's best-known books, the tale was included in the [[The Royal Ballet|Royal Ballet's]] ''[[The Tales of Beatrix Potter]].''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/culturenews/8203999/The-Tales-of-Beatrix-Potter-performed-by-The-Royal-Ballet.html|title=The Tales of Beatrix Potter performed by The Royal Ballet|last=Roberts|first=Laura|date=2010-12-16|work=Telegraph.co.uk|access-date=2017-06-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160821213751/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/culturenews/8203999/The-Tales-of-Beatrix-Potter-performed-by-The-Royal-Ballet.html|archive-date=2016-08-21|dead-url=|language=en}}</ref> It is the story of how Jemima, a domestic duck, is saved from a cunning fox who plans to kill her, when she tries to find a safe place for her eggs to hatch.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=nXYS8DlO6T4C|title=Tale of Jemima Puddle-Duck |last=Potter |first=Beatrix|date=1993 |publisher=Frederick Warne|isbn=9781854713858|language=en}}</ref>

=== In music ===

The domestic duck features in the musical composition ''[[Peter and the Wolf]]'', written by [[Sergei Prokofiev]] in 1936. The orchestra illustrates the [[Children's literature|children's story]] while the narrator tells it.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=vWTf_WPHkxQC&pg=PT24&dq |title=Duck|last=Rijke |first=Victoria de |date=2008 |publisher=Reaktion Books |isbn=978-1-861-89489-2}}</ref> In this, a domestic duck and a little bird argue on each other's flight capabilities. The duck is represented by the [[oboe]]. The story ends with the wolf eating the duck alive, its quack heard from inside the wolf's belly.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=9ITOQAAACAAJ|title=Peter and the Wolf |last=Prokofiev |first=Sergei |date=1999 |publisher=North-South Books |isbn=978-0-735-81189-8}}</ref>

=== In art ===
Domestic ducks are frequently depicted in wall paintings and grave objects from [[ancient Egypt]].<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=7w3bnoRf8VYC&pg=PA147&dq |title=The Great Gallery of Ducks and Other Waterfowl |last=LeMaster |first=Richard |date=March 1995 |publisher=Stackpole Books |isbn=978-0-811-70706-0}}</ref> They are featured in a range of ancient [[Artifact (archaeology)|artefacts]], which revealed that they were a fertility symbol.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=WgOGDAAAQBAJ |title=Birds: Myth, Lore and Legend |last=Chadd |first=Rachel Warren |last2=Taylor |first2=Marianne |date=2016 |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing |isbn=978-1-472-92287-8}}</ref>

[[File:Fried duck Bali.jpg|thumb|Fried duck Bali]]

=== As food ===
{{main|Duck (food)}}

Since ancient times, the duck has been eaten as food.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=KdR4jRJCxEsC&pg=PA124&dq |title=Food in the Ancient World from A to Z |last=Dalby |first=Andrew |date=2013 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-135-95422-2}}</ref> Usually only the breast and thigh meat is eaten.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=TOG-ItIHp_kC&pg=PA584&dq|title=The Visual Food Encyclopedia |date=1996 |publisher=Québec Amerique |isbn=978-2-764-40898-8}}</ref> It does not need to be [[Hanging (meat)|hung]] before preparation, and is often braised or roasted, sometimes flavoured with [[bitter orange]] or with [[port (wine)|port]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=pZ-1AQAAQBAJ&pg=PT1722&dq |title=The Oxford Companion to Food |last=Davidson |first=Alan |date=2006 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-191-01825-1 |page=472}}</ref> [[Peking duck]] is a dish of roast duck from [[Beijing]], China that has been prepared since medieval times. It is today traditionally served with [[spring pancake]]s, [[spring onion]]s and [[sweet bean sauce]].<ref>{{cite news |title=The Evolution of Peking Duck |work=CBS |date=24 September 2006 |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2006/09/24/sunday/main2036347.shtml}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pilotguides.com/destination_guide/asia/china/peking_duck.php |title=A Cultural Classic: Peking Duck|publisher=[[Globe Trekker]]|accessdate=26 June 2017}}</ref>

